       <p class="text-muted" style="max-width: 700px; margin-top: 8px;">
-        Browser WebSockets have no concept of "ownership." You call <code style="color:var(--cyan)">new WebSocket(url)</code>,
-        it exists in the global scope, and if your component unmounts you'd better remember to call <code style="color:var(--cyan)">ws.close()</code>
-        — otherwise you have a zombie connection leaking messages into nothing. In Asupersync, the WebSocket handle is
-        <strong style="color:var(--text);">scoped to a region</strong>. Close the region and the socket is automatically
-        closed with proper cleanup. The socket <em>cannot outlive its scope</em>.
-        This demo opens a real WebSocket, sends messages through the runtime, then closes the scope.
+        Browser resources (WebSockets, MessageChannels, streams) have no concept of "ownership." If your
+        component unmounts without explicitly closing them, they become zombies.
+        In Asupersync, resources are <strong style="color:var(--text);">scoped to a region</strong> with WASM tasks
+        tracking each end. Close the region and <em>everything under it</em> is torn down — ports closed, tasks released,
+        handles freed. The resource <em>cannot outlive its scope</em>.
+        This demo creates a real MessageChannel with WASM-tracked tasks, sends messages, then closes the scope.
       </p>
